  <section class="insentif-alpha-section">
    <div class="insentif-alpha-section-label">
      <span class="insentif-alpha-section-label-num">04</span>
      <span class="insentif-alpha-section-label-text">Decision Log</span>
      <span class="insentif-alpha-section-label-line"></span>
    </div>

    <div class="insentif-alpha-decision-list">

      <div class="insentif-alpha-decision-card">
        <div class="insentif-alpha-decision-header">
          <span class="insentif-alpha-decision-num">01</span>
          <div>
            <div class="insentif-alpha-decision-title">Typed DataSets / TableAdapters Instead of Modern ORM</div>
            <div class="insentif-alpha-decision-problem">The project was locked to .NET Framework 2.0 (corporate standard at Sanofi in 2013). Entity Framework 1.0 was available but immature and poorly suited for the complex stored procedure-heavy calculation logic required by the incentive engine.</div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="insentif-alpha-decision-body">
          <div>
            <div class="insentif-alpha-decision-col-label insentif-alpha-chosen"> Chosen — Typed DataSets</div>
            <div class="insentif-alpha-decision-col-text">TableAdapters provided strongly-typed data access with full stored procedure support. The visual designer made it easy to map 40+ tables. Queries were optimized for the incentive calculation engine. No ORM overhead — direct ADO.NET under the hood when needed.</div>
          </div>
          <div>
            <div class="insentif-alpha-decision-col-label insentif-alpha-tradeoff">△ Tradeoff — EF / NHibernate</div>
            <div class="insentif-alpha-decision-col-text">EF 1.0 on .NET 2.0 had limited LINQ support and poor stored procedure mapping. NHibernate required XML mapping files and had a steep learning curve. Neither would have handled the complex aggregate calculations efficiently.</div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="insentif-alpha-decision-code">
<pre><span class="insentif-alpha-token-cm">// Typed DataSet TableAdapter — strongly-typed data access</span>
<span class="insentif-alpha-token-type">IncentiveDataSet</span> ds = <span class="insentif-alpha-token-kw">new</span> <span class="insentif-alpha-token-fn">IncentiveDataSet</span>();
<span class="insentif-alpha-token-type">IncentiveDataSetTableAdapters</span>.<span class="insentif-alpha-token-type">TrnIncentiveTableAdapter</span> ta =
    <span class="insentif-alpha-token-kw">new</span> <span class="insentif-alpha-token-type">IncentiveDataSetTableAdapters</span>.<span class="insentif-alpha-token-fn">TrnIncentiveTableAdapter</span>();

ta.<span class="insentif-alpha-token-fn">FillByPeriod</span>(ds.TrnIncentive, year, month, <span class="insentif-alpha-token-str">"PHARMA"</span>);

<span class="insentif-alpha-token-cm">// Calculate incentive across all reps in the dataset</span>
<span class="insentif-alpha-token-kw">foreach</span> (<span class="insentif-alpha-token-type">IncentiveDataSet.TrnIncentiveRow</span> row <span class="insentif-alpha-token-kw">in</span> ds.TrnIncentive)
&#123;
    row.IncentiveAmount = <span class="insentif-alpha-token-fn">CalculateIncentive</span>(
        row.SalesAmount, row.TargetAmount, row.QualitativeScore);
&#125;</pre>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="insentif-alpha-decision-card">
        <div class="insentif-alpha-decision-header">
          <span class="insentif-alpha-decision-num">02</span>
          <div>
            <div class="insentif-alpha-decision-title">Windows Authentication vs Custom Forms Auth</div>
            <div class="insentif-alpha-decision-problem">Sanofi's IT environment was fully domain-joined with Active Directory. The system needed role-based access for ADMIN, Area Managers (AM), and Sales Managers (SM) without maintaining a separate user database.</div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="insentif-alpha-decision-body">
          <div>
            <div class="insentif-alpha-decision-col-label insentif-alpha-chosen"> Chosen — Windows Auth (Integrated)</div>
            <div class="insentif-alpha-decision-col-text">Leveraged Active Directory groups for role assignment. Zero password management — users authenticated with their corporate credentials. ASP.NET integrated Windows auth with URL-based role authorization via web.config. Seamless SSO for domain users.</div>
          </div>
          <div>
            <div class="insentif-alpha-decision-col-label insentif-alpha-tradeoff">△ Tradeoff — Forms Auth</div>
            <div class="insentif-alpha-decision-col-text">Would have required maintaining a separate user table, password policies, and login pages. No SSO — users would need yet another set of credentials. Increased support burden for password resets and account management.</div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="insentif-alpha-decision-code">
<pre><span class="insentif-alpha-token-cm">// Web.config — Windows Auth with role-based URL authorization</span>
&lt;authentication mode=<span class="insentif-alpha-token-str">"Windows"</span> /&gt;
&lt;authorization&gt;
  &lt;deny users=<span class="insentif-alpha-token-str">"?"</span> /&gt;
&lt;/authorization&gt;

<span class="insentif-alpha-token-cm">// Role-based access for admin area</span>
&lt;location path=<span class="insentif-alpha-token-str">"Admin"</span>&gt;
  &lt;system.web&gt;
    &lt;authorization&gt;
      &lt;allow roles=<span class="insentif-alpha-token-str">"SANOFI\ALPHA_ADMIN"</span> /&gt;
      &lt;deny users=<span class="insentif-alpha-token-str">"*"</span> /&gt;
    &lt;/authorization&gt;
  &lt;/system.web&gt;
&lt;/location&gt;</pre>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="insentif-alpha-decision-card">
        <div class="insentif-alpha-decision-header">
          <span class="insentif-alpha-decision-num">03</span>
          <div>
            <div class="insentif-alpha-decision-title">SSRS RDLC for Reporting Instead of Custom Reports</div>
            <div class="insentif-alpha-decision-problem">The system required complex incentive reports with drill-down capability, export to Excel/PDF, and printed layouts for management sign-off. Building a custom reporting engine would have been prohibitively expensive.</div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="insentif-alpha-decision-body">
          <div>
            <div class="insentif-alpha-decision-col-label insentif-alpha-chosen"> Chosen — SSRS RDLC (Local Mode)</div>
            <div class="insentif-alpha-decision-col-text">SQL Server Reporting Services (RDLC) provided professional-grade reports with drill-down, sorting, and export. Integrated directly with Typed DataSets for strongly-typed report binding. Report Viewer control embedded in ASPX pages. No separate SSRS server required.</div>
          </div>
          <div>
            <div class="insentif-alpha-decision-col-label insentif-alpha-tradeoff">△ Tradeoff — Custom Reports</div>
            <div class="insentif-alpha-decision-col-text">Full control over rendering and layout, but would have required building pagination, export, and drill-down from scratch. Crystal Reports was considered but required additional licensing and runtime deployment.</div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="insentif-alpha-decision-code">
<pre><span class="insentif-alpha-token-cm">// RDLC report binding with Typed DataSet</span>
<span class="insentif-alpha-token-type">ReportViewer1</span>.LocalReport.ReportPath = <span class="insentif-alpha-token-str">"Reports/IncentiveSummary.rdlc"</span>;
<span class="insentif-alpha-token-type">ReportViewer1</span>.LocalReport.DataSources.Clear();

<span class="insentif-alpha-token-type">ReportDataSource</span> rds = <span class="insentif-alpha-token-kw">new</span> <span class="insentif-alpha-token-fn">ReportDataSource</span>(
